This paper focuses on the relationship between gender, linguistic style, and social networks using a corpus of Twitter users. The study involves clustering Twitter users based on their language use and identifying individuals whose language does not match the population-level gender patterns. This work involves natural language processing (NLP) techniques and social network analysis, which are relevant to the sub-categories of computational linguistics (cs.CL), social and information networks (cs.SI), social dynamics (cs.SD), social and economic systems (cs.SOC), and machine learning (cs.LG). Therefore, these are the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories for this paper.
